 style=''background-color: #e9e9e9;''\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\n''Random! Cartoons'' is the third [[Frederator Studios]] short cartoon shorts \"incubator\". Frederator has persisted in the tradition of surfacing new talent, characters and series with several cartoon shorts \"incubators,\" including (as of 2016): ''[[What a Cartoon!]]'' ([[Cartoon Network]], 1995), ''The Meth Minute 39'' ([[Channel Frederator]], 2008),<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL74F257B28D3C60DA The Meth Minute 39 on YouTube]</ref> ''Random! Cartoons'' ([[Nickelodeon]]/[[Nicktoons (United States)|Nicktoons]], 2008), ''[[Too Cool! Cartoons]]'' ([[Cartoon Hangover]], 2012), and ''GO! Cartoons'' (Cartoon Hangover, 2016).<ref>[http://deadline.com/2014/11/sony-pictures-animation-fred-seibert-cartoon-hangover-incubator-1201271591/ Sony, Channel Frederator Launch Online Animation Incubator, by David Bloom, Deadline Hollywood, November 3, 2014]</ref> These laboratories have spun off notable series like: ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'', ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'', ''[[Johnny Bravo]]'', ''[[Cow & Chicken]]'', ''[[Courage the Cowardly Dog]]'', ''[[The Fairly OddParents]]'', ''Nite Fite'', ''[[Fanboy & Chum Chum]]'', ''[[Adventure Time]]'', ''[[Bravest Warriors]]'', ''Rocket Dog'', and ''[[Bee and PuppyCat]]''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{main|Frederator Cartoon Shorts Filmography}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television|United States|Cartoon|Nickelodeon}}\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n*''[[Spike and Mike's Festival of Animation]]''\n*''[[Liquid Television]]''\n*''[[Raw Toonage]]''\n*''[[What a Cartoon!]]''\n*''[[KaBlam!]]''\n*''[[Cartoon Sushi]]''\n*''[[Oh Yeah! Cartoons]]''\n*''[[Exposure (American TV series)|Exposure]]''\n*''[[Eye Drops]]''\n*''[[VH1 ILL-ustrated]]''\n*''[[Nicktoons Film Festival]]''\n*''[[Sunday Pants]]''\n*''[[Shorty McShorts' Shorts]]''\n*''[[Wedgies (Cartoon Network)|Wedgies]]''\n*''[[Shorts in a Bunch]]''\n*''[[The Cartoonstitute]]''\n*''[[Off the Air (TV series)|Off the Air]]''\n*''[[Nickelodeon Animated Shorts Program]]''\n*''[[Too Cool! Cartoons]]''\n*''[[Cartoon Network Shorts Department]]''\n*''[[TripTank]]''\n*''[[Disney XD Shortstop]]''\n*''[[Go! Cartoons]]''\n*''[[Love, Death & Robots]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://imdb.com/title/tt0890874/episodes#season-1 Episode list] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n* [http://www.hornswiggle.com Official Hornswiggle site]\n* [http://www.junworks.com/kr.html Official Kyle+Rosemary site]\n* {{IMDb title|0890874|Random! Cartoons}}\n* [http://www.milowerx.com/personal-films/flavio Official Flavio cartoon site]\n\n{{Frederator Studios}}\n{{Adventure Time}}\n\n[[Category:2008 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2009 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated anthology television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American flash animated television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Frederator Studios]]\n[[Category:Nicktoons]]\n[[Category:Nicktoons original programming]]\n", "name_user": "G30381004", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(added external links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random!_Cartoons"}
{"title_page": "Patricia Belcher", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Patricia Belcher\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|04|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Helena, Montana]], U.S. \n| occupation = Film, television and stage actress\n| years_active = 1984\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Patricia Belcher''' (born April 7, 1954) is an American actress, known for her roles as Ms. Dabney in the [[Disney Channel]] sitcom ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'', and as [[federal prosecutor|United States Attorney]] Caroline Julian in the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] [[crime procedural]] comedy-drama series ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' (2005\u20132017).\n\n==Life and career==\nBelcher was born in Helena, Montana. She is of [[African American]] descent.<ref>{{cite book|title=Horror Noire: Blacks in American Horror Films from the 1890s to Present|author=Coleman, Robin R. Means|page=153}}</ref> Prior to becoming an actress, Belcher was a contestant on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' losing to then attorney Ron Black in one of his 5 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeopardy.com/minisites/tocyearbook/#1985|title=Jeopardy! Tournament Champions Archive - Best Jeopardy! Players|publisher=|accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref> She studied acting under the guidance of many drama teachers, including the Oscar-nominated actress, [[Beah Richards]].\n\nBelcher is known for playing judges, doctors, nurses, government officials, and other authority figures, often to comic effect. She has made many appearances in films and television series including ''[[The Number 23]]'', ''[[Unknown (2006 film)|Unknown]]'', ''[[Jeepers Creepers (2001 film)|Jeepers Creepers]]'', ''[[Heartbreakers (2001 film)|Heartbreakers]]'' and ''[[(500) Days of Summer]]''. She also has made appearances in television series, including ''[[Everybody Loves Raymond]]'', ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'', ''[[Boston Legal]]'', ''[[The Jake Effect]]'', ''[[Twins (TV series)|Twins]]'', ''[[The Proud Family]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Sister, Sister (TV series)|Sister, Sister]]'', ''[[In Plain Sight]]'', ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'', ''[[It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia]]'', ''[[Still Standing (TV series)|Still Sitting down]]'', ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]'', ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' and ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''. She is also one of the most active actors appearing in commercials. Products include [[GEICO]], [[Staples Inc.|Staples]], [[Time Warner]], [[American Cancer Society]] and [[Wells Fargo]].\n\nIn 2001, Belcher was cast as Jezelle Gay Hartman, a psychic, in the [[horror film]] ''[[Jeepers Creepers (2001 film)|Jeepers Creepers]]''. The film received mixed reviews from critics, however received positive awards from audiences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jeepers_creepers/|title=Jeepers Creepers (2001)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=2014-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jeepers-creepers|title=Jeepers Creepers|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2014-07-25}}</ref> \nThe film was a commercial success,  opening in 2,944 theaters and took in a domestic gross of $37,904,175; it later made $21,313,614 internationally, making a total of $59,217,789 worldwide.<ref name=mojo>[https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jeeperscreepers.htm Jeepers Creepers (2001)]. ''[[Box Office Mojo]]''. Retrieved 2010-10-24.</ref> In 2003, Belcher was originally going to appear again as Jezelle Gay Hartman in ''[[Jeepers Creepers 2]]'', as the plot was about her character and [[Gina Philips]]' character hunting down The Creeper, while a school bus full of teens terrorized by The Creeper was just a subplot. But the more writer and director [[Victor Salva]] worked on the script, the more the bus plot became more interesting. So he decide to scrap both her and Philip's plot and concentrate the film on the bus instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/title/tt0301470/trivia?ref_=m_tt_trv_trv|title=Jeepers Creepers II (2003)|work=IMDb|accessdate=13 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2006 until 2017, she recurred on ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]'' as attorney [[Caroline Julian]]. \nBelcher produced her 2008 role in the film ''Lower Learning'' as Colette.\n\nIn 2009, she played Millie in the romantic comedy ''[[(500) Days of Summer]]''. The film received positive reviews from critics upon its release. Based on over 214 professional reviews, it obtained a \"Certified Fresh\" seal on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with an approval rating of 86% and an average score of 7.6 out of 10. The film was a box office success as well, becoming a  \"[[sleeper hit]]\" and earning over $60 million in worldwide returns, far exceeding its $7.5 million budget. Also that year through 2010, Belcher had a recurring role on [[Better Off Ted]] as Janet S. Crotum, the head of human resources of Veridian Dynamics. \nOn May 13, 2010, [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] officially canceled the series due to low viewing figures.<ref name=\"FF\">{{cite web|title=Report: FlashForward, ''Romantically Challenged'', ''Better Off Ted'', ''Scrubs'' Canceled |url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/05/13/report-flashforward-romantically-challenged-better-off-ted-scrubs/51371|accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref> After the cancellation of ''Better Off Ted'' Belcher moved on and began another recurring role on the [[Disney Channel]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'', playing the strict and easily annoyed neighbor, Mrs. Estelle Dabney.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Kit and Kaboodle|episodelink=List of Good Luck Charlie episodes#ep12|series=Good Luck Charlie|network=[[Disney Channel]]|airdate=July 11, 2010|season=1|number=12|minutes=11:28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she appeared as Ingrid in ''[[Bad Words (film)|Bad Words]]'', and she voiced Chimamanda Lobo in the video game ''[[Dead Island: Riptide]]''. After four seasons the show ''Good Luck Charlie'' ended on February 16, 2014, with a one-hour finale.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/06/good-luck-charlie-cancelled-three-seasons-disney-channel/ |title=Disney Channel's 'Good Luck Charlie' To End Its Run |publisher=Deadline.com |date= |accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=TVGfinale>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Good-Luck-Charlie-Finale-1076386.aspx |title=Exclusive: Disney Channel Schedules Good Luck Charlie Finale |date=January 21, 2014 |accessdate=January 22, 2014 |first=Michael |last=Schneider |work=TV Guide}}</ref> Later that year Belcher again teamed with ''Jeepers Creepers'' writer and director [[Victor Salva]] for his horror film ''[[Dark House (2014 film)|Dark House]]''. As well as appearing on ''[[The Millers]]'', and ''[[Partners (2014 TV series)|Partners]]''.\n\nIn 2015, she appeared in the GEICO commercial with the band Europe. She was Grandmother in Wells Fargo's 2017 commercial 'Lost Debit Card.'  She also appeared in 2 other GEICO commercials once as a DMV picture taker and most recently a waitress in a 24 hour diner.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Flatliners]]'' \n| Edna\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Clear and Present Danger (film)|Clear and Present Danger]]''\n| INS Officer \n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Species (film)|Species]]''\n| Hospital Admittance Clerk  \n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Lawnmower Man 2: Beyond Cyberspace]]''\n| Impatient Customer \n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Eye for an Eye (1996 film)|Eye for an Eye]]''\n| Quarreling Woman \n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Message in a Bottle (film)|Message in a Bottle]]''\n| Annie\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Molly (1999 film)|Molly]]''\n| Margaret Duffy \n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[The Wood]]''\n| Mrs. Huges \n| \n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Heartbreakers (2001 film)|Heartbreakers]]''\n| Hotel Housekeeping Maid\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Jeepers Creepers (2001 film)|Jeepers Creepers]]''\n| Jezelle Gay Hartman \n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''The Board Room''\n| Stephens  \n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Spin, Shoot & Run''\n| Abagail \n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[I Love Your W